import TokensExercise from "./_components/TokensExercise.astro";
import LinkContainer from "@/components/Articles/Links/LinkContainer.astro";
---

<Chapter title="What is a Token?">
  <Heading>How we communicate with Redis?</Heading>

  <Prose>
    <p>
      If you have used <strong>Redis</strong> before, you know that it follows a
      traditional <strong>Client-Server architecture.</strong> One or many Redis
      Clients send commands like <Keyword word="GET" />, <Keyword word="SET" />,
      or <Keyword word="DEL" /> to a single central <strong
        >Redis Server.</strong
      > The server reads the command from the connection, parses it, evaluates it,
      and writes the response back to the client.
    </p>

    <p>
      For the server to understand a command, it first needs to transform it
      into a meaningful representation — rather than treating it as plain text.
      That process is called <strong>Parsing.</strong>
    </p>

    <p>
      So, before we can evaluate a Command, we are going to transform it twice
      into more accessible representations:
    </p>

    <Picture
      class="w-full my-40"
      loading="eager"
      src="/articles/commands-transformations.svg"
      alt="Commands transformations"
      size={514}
    />

    <p>
      The first transformation is turning our <strong>Raw Command</strong> into <Keyword
        word="Tokens"
      />, which are the <strong>atomic units</strong> that compose a Command Representation.

      <br />
      The process of turning raw text into meaningful Tokens is called <strong
        >Lexical Analysis</strong
      >, and it's done by a <Keyword word="Lexer" />.
    </p>

    <p>For example, if we feed this command to our <Keyword word="Lexer" />:</p>

    <SETExample />

    <p>
      What comes out of our <Keyword word="Lexer" /> looks something like this:
    </p>

    <SETTokens />

    <p>
      Notice that not all Tokens are equal. <Keyword word="SET" /> is a <strong
        >command token</strong
      >
      — it represents the operation we want to perform. <Keyword
        word=`Identifier("userName")`
      />
      and <Keyword word=`Identifier("Alejandro")` /> are <strong
        >identifier tokens</strong
      > — they carry the arguments. Each Token knows both <strong
        >what kind it is</strong
      > and <strong>what it contains.</strong>
    </p>

    <p>This is the theory — let's take a look at the code!</p>

    <h3 class="fraunces">Defining Tokens</h3>

    <p>
      There are <strong>several kinds</strong> of Tokens our system should handle:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Commands:</strong> The instructions (e.g., <Keyword
          word="GET"
        />, <Keyword word="SET" />, <Keyword word="PING" />).
      </li>

      <li>
        <strong>Identifiers:</strong> The keys or values (e.g., <Keyword
          word="userName"
        />, <Keyword word="Alejandro" />).
      </li>

      <li>
        <strong>Numbers:</strong> Numeric values used in operations (e.g., <Keyword
          word="100"
        />).
      </li>
    </ul>

    <Picture
      src="/articles/token-example.svg"
      alt="Command tokens"
      size={1024}
    />

    <p>
      As shown in the diagram above, the command <Keyword
        word="SET userName Alejandro"
      /> is not treated as one long string. Instead, the Lexer identifies <strong
        >three distinct</strong
      >
      Tokens: a <Keyword word="SET" /> command token followed by two <Keyword
        word="Identifier"
      /> tokens.
    </p>

    <p>
      The <strong>kind</strong> of these Tokens is called <Keyword
        word="TokenKind"
      />, and it's the <strong>first entity</strong> that we will define in our Project!
    </p>

    <h3 class="fraunces my-20">Defining TokenKinds</h3>

    <p>
      Now that we've establish the concept of a Token, we need a way to
      categorize them in code. We will create a <Keyword word="TokenKind" /> type
      to represent every possible category our Lexer might encounter — such as <Keyword
        word="Commands"
      />, <Keyword word="Identifiers" />, or <Keyword word="Numbers" />. We'll
      also include <strong>special</strong> TokenKinds that every Lexer needs.
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <Keyword word="EOF" />: Stands for <strong>End Of File</strong> and signals
        that there is no more input to read.
      </li>
      <li>
        <Keyword word="ILLEGAL" />: represents any character our Lexer doesn't
        recognize.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>Enough theory — it's time to write our first lines of code.</p>

    <Tokens />

    <strong>
      Why use a <Keyword word="byte" /> for <Keyword word="TokenKind" />?
    </strong>

    <p>
      You might wonder why we chose a <Keyword word="byte" /> instead of a <Keyword
        word="string"
      />
      or a standard <Keyword word="int" />. There are two primary engineering
      reasons:
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        <strong>Memory Efficiency:</strong> Since our Lexer will generate a new instance
        for every single word or symbol in a command, using a <strong
          >1-byte</strong
        > type keeps our memory footprint as small as possible.
      </li>

      <li>
        <strong>Sufficient Capacity:</strong> A <Keyword word="byte" /> ( an alias
        for <Keyword word="uint8" /> ) can represent up to 256 unique values. Since
        our Redis clone will only have a few dozen command types and symbols, this
        is the perfect, lightweight fit for our <Keyword word="TokenKind" />.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p>
      With our <Keyword word="TokenKind" /> defined, we now need a container to hold
      two things: the <strong>kind of token</strong> it is, and the <strong
        >raw text</strong
      > it was derived from — which we'll call the <Keyword word="Literal" />.
    </p>

    <TokenStruct />

    <p>The <Keyword word="Token" /> <strong>struct</strong> is composed of:</p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        <Keyword word="kind" />: The <Keyword word="TokenKind" /> that tells the
        <Keyword word="Lexer" /> how to interpret the token — whether it's a command,
        an identifier, or something else entirely.
      </li>

      <li>
        <Keyword word="Literal" />: The <strong>raw string</strong> value extracted
        from the input (e.g., <Keyword word="GET" /> or <Keyword
          word="mykey"
        />).
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p>
      🔥 <strong>Fun Fact:</strong> Even thought i just said that the <Keyword
        word="Token"
      /> struct should be as lightweight as possible, this is not the <strong
        >most lightweight representation</strong
      > for a Token.
    </p>

    <p>
      The <strong>Golang Parser</strong> uses an amazing technique: instead of storing
      a piece of text in the struct as we do, they just store the <strong
        >indices</strong
      > from where the piece of text beings and ends, a simple and ingenious trick
      if you want to implement it, <a
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
        href="https://github.com/golang/go/blob/3fd729b2a14a7efcf08465cbea60a74da5457f06/src/go/token/position.go#L83"
        >Check the details here</a
      >.
    </p>
  </Prose>

  <TokensExercise />

  <Prose>
    <p>
      In the next chapter, we will build the <Keyword word="Lexer" /> — the engine
      responsible for turning a raw <strong>Redis command</strong> into exactly these
      <strong>tokens</strong>.
    </p>
  </Prose>

  <LinkContainer prevSection="requirements" nextSection="lexer" />
</Chapter>
